snippet.textDisplay: Next time you make bread, proof the yeast with just a pinch of sugar in a couple tablespooons of warm water.  Never add salt to your yeast mixture.  Add salt to the flour and mix the proofed yeast into the flour with the other wet ingredients.  Salt can kill your yeast and cause your bread not to rise as much.  This is specially important when using an expired yeast as not all of the yeast in the package will be alive still.  Yeast will also stay better for much longer if stored in the fridge.

snippet.textDisplay: Fun fact! I went to Old Sturbridge Village in Massachusetts last year. They were explaining to us how people used to make yeast traps to collect wild yeast. Can't really remember the process but, once collected it would be made into a cake and put near the hearth to dry out. When they were ready to make bread, they'd break some off and proof it to see if it would work. You could go through a multi-day process of collecting and drying yeast only to have it not work! Quarantine doesn't sound too bad compared to the 1830s!

snippet.textDisplay: the true french bread : 500g floor, 12g salt, 15g dry yeast and 40ml water. mix the dry ingredients together, add the water. work the dough during 10 minutes, when the dough is not sticky, let it rest during 1/2h. Work again the dough to make gazes out, cut it in pieces you want, 1 bread/6 breads. Let it rest again for 1h. work again a little bit. Oven on 220/240 degree celcius. Cook it until for 30minutes, ajust the time if needed, each oven is different .
